Revised: April 2, 2018

Published: April 3, 2018 Ferrous $\left(\left[\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}\right]^{4-}\right)$ and ferric $\left(\left[\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}\right]^{3-}\right)$ hexacyanide complexes serve as prototypical model systems for understanding the structure and spectroscopy of $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{II})$ and $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{III})$ octahedral transition-metal complexes in solution and have been the subject of several studies. ${ }^{2-14}$ Along with equilibrium ground-state studies, the photochemistry of the $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{II})$ and $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{III})$ complexes in solution has been studied with ultrafast IR, optical, and X-ray probes, revealing the role of coupled electronic and vibrational dynamics, ${ }^{15,16}$ nonequilibrium vibrational energy relaxation following charge-transfer excitation, ${ }^{17-19}$ photoaquation mechanisms, ${ }^{20,21}$ and core and valence orbital changes following photo-oxidation. ${ }^{13,17,22}$ In this paper, we focus on ground-state spectroscopic and computational studies of the hexacyanoferrate complexes in water. The effect of water and its varying hydrogen bonding interactions with the $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{II})$ and $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{III})$ complexes on the vibrational frequency and dynamics of the high-frequency cyanide stretching modes have been explored with nonlinear IR spectroscopy combined with classical molecular dynamics (MD) simulations. ${ }^{2,3}$ Various X-ray absorption (XA) and emission techniques have been used to probe the oxidation state and local electronic and geometric structure around the Fe atom in the $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{II})$ and $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{III})$ complexes in water. ${ }^{5,7,9-11,13}$ Iron L-edge and N K-edge resonant inelastic X-ray scattering (RIXS) experiments show that $\pi$-back-bonding is slightly stronger in the $\mathrm{Fe}$ (II) complex compared with the $\mathrm{Fe}$ (III) complex dissolved in water and have been interpreted using restricted active space second-order perturbation theory (RASPT2) calculations without including explicit solvation. ${ }^{10}$ Another RIXS study of the Fe L-edge and N K-edge for the aqueous $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{II})$ complex also probed metal-ligand interactions and was combined with the restricted active space selfconsistent first- and second-order perturbation theory (RASSCF/RASPT2) simulations also without including explicit solvation. ${ }^{5}$ The role of the solvent and its effect on pre-edge absorption transitions at the Fe K-edge was explored by Penfold et al. by measuring Fe K $\alpha$ RIXS of the $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{II})$ and $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{III})$ complexes dissolved in water and ethylene glycol. ${ }^{7} \mathrm{MD}$ simulations were used to understand how the local solvation structure around the $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{II})$ and $\mathrm{Fe}$ (III) complexes varied as a function of the solvent.

Although the spectroscopy of hexacyanoferrate complexes in solution has been the subject of several experimental studies, most of the previous works have focused on a narrow energy window, as described above. The accompanying computations of the spectroscopic observables on these solvated transitionmetal model systems have similarly focused on a narrow energy region, and the majority of the computations have either been in the gas phase or in combination with an implicit solvent treatment. Here, we present a combined experimental and computational study of hexacyanoferrate aqueous complexes at equilibrium. Our experiments span the range of $250 \mathrm{meV}$ to $7.15 \mathrm{keV}$ and include the IR spectroscopy of the cyanide stretching modes, the optical absorption spectroscopy of the charge-transfer transitions, element-specific XA spectroscopy at the Fe K-edge, and valence-to-core X-ray emission spectroscopy (VtC-XES). To understand how the local solvation environment influences the geometric and electronic structure and therefore the spectroscopic signatures of these complexes, we combine explicit solvent effects via the density functional theory (DFT)-based quantum mechanics/molecular mechanics (QM/MM) MD with spectroscopic calculations of the experiments spanning the IR to X-ray wavelengths. To the best of our knowledge, spectroscopy calculations spanning these wavelengths using explicit solute-solvent configurations from MD simulations and performed within a consistent computational approach have not been previously reported for these systems. The present work also serves as a reference benchmark for our ongoing equilibrium and transient studies on a series of cyanide-bridged transition-metal mixed valence complexes: $\left[\left(\mathrm{NH}_{3}\right)_{5} \mathrm{Ru}^{\mathrm{III}} \mathrm{NCFe}^{\mathrm{II}}(\mathrm{CN})_{5}\right]^{-}$, trans$\left[(\mathrm{NC})_{5} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{II}} \mathrm{CNPt}^{\mathrm{IV}}\left(\mathrm{NH}_{3}\right)_{4} \mathrm{NCFe}^{\mathrm{II}}(\mathrm{CN})_{5}\right]^{4-}$, and trans$\left[(\mathrm{NC})_{5} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{III}} \mathrm{CNRu}{ }^{\mathrm{II}}(\mathrm{L})_{4} \mathrm{NCFe}^{\mathrm{III}}(\mathrm{CN})_{5}\right]^{4-}(\mathrm{L}=$ pyridine $)$.

\section{MATERIALS AND METHODS}
Potassium ferrocyanide $\left(\mathrm{K}_{4} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{II}}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}\right)$ and ferricyanide $\left(\mathrm{K}_{3} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{III}}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}\right)$ compounds were purchased from SigmaAldrich and used without further purification.

2.1. Infrared Spectroscopy. Aqueous $100 \mathrm{mM}$ solutions of the $\mathrm{K}_{4} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{II}}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}$ and $\mathrm{K}_{3} \mathrm{Fe}^{\text {III }}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}$ complexes were prepared for taking IR spectra of the cyanide stretching $\left(\nu_{\mathrm{CN}}\right)$ region. A JASCO FT/IR 4100 instrument was used to collect the steadystate IR spectra of the aqueous sample solutions with a spectral resolution of $2 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$. The water background from the IR spectra of the hexacyanoferrate complexes was removed by subtracting an IR spectrum of the solvent taken under the same conditions.

2.2. UV/Vis Spectroscopy. A JASCO V630 spectrometer with a spectral resolution of $0.5 \mathrm{~nm}$ was used to collect the steady-state electronic UV/vis spectra of 14 and $21 \mathrm{mM}$ aqueous solutions of the $\mathrm{K}_{4} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{II}}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}$ and $\mathrm{K}_{3} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{III}}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}$ complexes, respectively.

2.3. X-ray Spectroscopy and Data Analysis. Measurements of the valence-to-core $\mathrm{X}$-ray emission were carried out at beamline 7-ID-D of the Advanced Photon Source at Argonne National Laboratory using a 24-bunch fill mode. ${ }^{23}$ Samples of $\mathrm{K}_{4} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{II}}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}$ and $\mathrm{K}_{3} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{III}}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}$ were prepared as $400 \mathrm{mM}$ solutions in distilled water. The samples were continuously refreshed using a sapphire nozzle jet that produced a liquid sheet of $200 \mu \mathrm{m}$ thickness at a $45^{\circ}$ angle relative to the incident $\mathrm{X}$-rays. The sample was exposed to monochromatic $\mathrm{X}$-rays with a $7.5 \mathrm{keV}$ incident energy and $0.4 \mathrm{eV}$ monochromator resolution, focused to a spot size of $5 \times 5 \mu \mathrm{m}^{2}$. Emitted Xrays were dispersed using a $\mathrm{Si}(531)$ crystal analyzer $(2.5 \times 10$ $\left.\mathrm{cm}^{2}\right)$ in the von Hamos geometry with a $25 \mathrm{~cm}$ focusing radius in the nondispersive plane (fabricated by the Optics Group at the Advanced Photon Source). Diffracted X-rays were recorded using a silicon diode array detector (Mythen). The entire spectrometer was enclosed in a $\mathrm{He}$ environment. Energy calibration of the spectrometer was achieved by the elastic scattering of the incident X-rays at multiple energies. The spectrometer resolution was determined to be $1 \mathrm{eV}$ fwhm. Each emission spectrum was accumulated for $180 \mathrm{~s}$, and the data presented here are the averaged results of 32 spectra for each sample.

Iron K-edge XA spectra were acquired at beamline 10.3.2 of the Advanced Light Source at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory. ${ }^{24}$ Samples of $\mathrm{K}_{4} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{II}}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}$ and $\mathrm{K}_{3} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{III}}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}$ were prepared as $40 \mathrm{mM}$ solutions in distilled water. To prevent changes in the spectra because of sample degradation from the X-rays, we utilized a low-volume flowing sample cell made with X-ray capillary cuvettes. Quartz capillary cuvettes with a $10 \mu \mathrm{m}$ wall thickness and $300 \mu \mathrm{m}$ OD (Hampton Research, HR6-132) were cleaved and glued to flexible tubing and mounted on a fabricated sample holder. Liquid sample flowed through the capillary tubes with flow rates of $6 \mathrm{~mL} / \mathrm{min}$ using a small piezoelectric pump (Bartels microComponents, MP6), and the total sample volume was $\sim 3 \mathrm{~mL}$. To prevent contamination, each sample used a separate set of capillary tubes. Monochromatic X-rays at $\sim 7 \mathrm{keV}$ impinged on the samples with a spot size of $16 \times 7 \mu \mathrm{m}^{2}$. Sample capillary tubes were mounted to accommodate fluorescence detection at $90^{\circ}$ from the incident X-rays. X-ray fluorescence was detected on an Amptek silicon drift diode. The incident X-ray energy was scanned over a range of $1 \mathrm{keV}$ to cover the XA near-edge structure (XANES) and extended XA fine structure (EXAFS) region at the $\mathrm{Fe}$ K-edge.

Data reduction of the raw steady-state XA signal was performed according to standard procedures, using the Athena program. ${ }^{25,26}$ The theoretical scattering functions for the EXAFS signal were calculated with FEFF $8.20^{27}$ using structures of the $\mathrm{K}_{4} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{II}}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}$ and $\mathrm{K}_{3} \mathrm{Fe}^{\mathrm{III}}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}$ complexes obtained from snapshots of the MD simulations described below. The fitting of the EXAFS data was performed using WinXAS 3.0.4. ${ }^{28}$ For this purpose, $k^{3}$-weighted EXAFS spectra were Fourier transformed over the $2-11 \AA^{-1}$ range using a Bessel window. The fits are performed to both the real and imaginary part of the data in the region of $0.7<R<3.5(\AA)$. The following parameters were allowed to vary in the fitting routine: the distances of the $\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{C}$ and the $\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{N}$ singlescattering paths, the corresponding Debye-Waller factors $\left(\sigma^{2}\right)$, and the amplitude reduction factor $\left(S_{0}^{2}\right)$. The coordination number was held constant at six for both of the single scattering paths of $\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{C}$ and $\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{N}$. The fit also included the $\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{N}$ multiple scattering paths. The coordination number, distance, and Debye-Waller factor of the multiple scattering paths were correlated with the single scattering paths in the fitting routine. The error bars on the best-fit parameters are statistical errors extracted from the WinXAS program.

2.4. Computational Details. All calculations were performed with the NWChem computational chemistry package. ${ }^{29}$ To study the solvated model transition-metal complexes $\left[\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}\right]^{3-}$ and $\left[\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}\right]^{4-}$ in aqueous solution, we have performed extensive hybrid $\mathrm{QM} / \mathrm{MM} M \mathrm{MD}$ simulations. Single $\left[\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}\right]^{3-}$ and $\left[\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}\right]^{4-}$ anions were placed in a cubic box and solvated with 4184 and 4182 water molecules, respectively, from a previously equilibrated bulk water "template" system, having a density of $1 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$ (water density at the standard temperature-pressure). The resulting box size for both systems was $49.98 \AA \times 49.98 \AA \times 49.98 \AA$. Three $\mathrm{K}^{+}$ cations and four $\mathrm{K}^{+}$cations were randomly placed (approximately $15 \AA$ away from the anion) in the solvation environment for $\left[\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}\right]^{3-}$ and $\left[\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{CN})_{6}\right]^{4-}$ complex systems, respectively, to provide an overall neutral charge for the entire solvated system. The $\mathrm{K}$ counter ions were allowed to move freely. Each transition-metal complex was treated quantum mechanically $(\mathrm{QM})$, whereas the rest of the system (the water bath) was treated at the MM level. This partitioning avoids the need for on-the-fly adaptive reassignment of atoms as $\mathrm{QM}$ or MM during the MD simulations, which is especially challenging in simulations where solvent exchange is possible between the $\mathrm{QM}$ and $\mathrm{MM}$ subsystems.

The water molecules and potassium cations, which comprise the MM region, were treated with the SPC/E water $\operatorname{model}^{30}$ and SPC/E-specific $\mathrm{K}^{+}$force field of Joung and Cheatham, ${ }^{31}$ respectively. For the $\mathrm{QM}$ region, the $6-311 \mathrm{G}^{* *}$ basis set $^{32,33}$ was used for the $\mathrm{C}$ and $\mathrm{N}$ atoms, and the Stuttgart basis set/ relativistic small-core effective core potential $(\mathrm{ECP})^{34}$ was assigned to the $\mathrm{Fe}$ atom. Lennard-Jones parameters were assigned to the atoms of the complex for the nonbonding van der Waals interaction with the water molecules. Specifically, SPC/E-compatible GAFF (generalized AMBER force field) Lennard-Jones parameters were used for the C ("c1") and $\mathrm{N}$ ("n1") atoms, and the Lennard-Jones "feo" parameters of CLAYFF $^{36}$ were used for the tight octahedral environment of the Fe atom.

Prior to running MD, both systems were annealed through a series of freeze and thaw cycles of the complex and solvent until the energy change was less than $0.0001$ Hartrees. Five freeze and thaw cycles were used for both solution systems. Following the annealing phase, QM/MM MD was performed at $298.15 \mathrm{~K}$ $(N V T)$ for 20 ps after a 1 ps equilibration with a time step of $0.25$ fs. For the SPC/E water model, the SHAKE algorithm ${ }^{37}$ was used to keep the water molecules rigid (constraining the bond lengths and bond angle). The QM region (i.e., complexes) was described at the DFT level of theory with the global hybrid PBE0 (25\% Hartree-Fock exchange) exchange-correlation functional. ${ }^{38}$ The complexes, which comprise the $\mathrm{QM}$ region in the models, were allowed to move freely (i.e., the SHAKE method was not applied).

Structural models for inputs to our spectroscopy calculations were obtained from QM/MM MD snapshots following equilibration. These snapshots included the transition-metal complex along with an explicit solvation environment. For the IR simulations, 20 snapshots were further optimized, and a harmonic frequency analysis was performed in the full $\mathrm{QM} /$ $\mathrm{MM}$ environment. The harmonic frequency intensities from the 20 snapshots were combined to generate an IR spectrum. For the UV/vis and X-ray spectroscopy calculations, full QM calculations were performed on 10 explicitly solvated model clusters that were extracted from the same snapshots used in the IR simulations. These clusters (i.e., for the UV/vis and Xray calculations) were constructed by taking the transitionmetal complex center as well as the $4 \AA$ thick shell of explicit water molecules surrounding the complex, corresponding to a total of 133 atoms including 40 water molecules, respectively, for each complex.

The UV/vis spectra were calculated with time-dependent DFT (TDDFT), ${ }^{39,40}$ whereas the Fe K-edge XANES spectra of the two complexes were calculated using restricted excitation window $\operatorname{TDDFT}^{41-46}$ including multipole contributions to the oscillator strengths. This approach, which involves defining a restricted subspace of single excitations from the relevant core orbitals and no restrictions on the target unoccupied states, is valid because excitations from the deep-core states are wellseparated from pure valence-level excitations. We have successfully used this approach in several studies including the K-edges of oxygen, carbon, and fluorine in a number of molecular systems; ${ }^{45}$ ruthenium $\mathrm{L}_{3}$-edge in a series of model $\mathrm{Ru}(\mathrm{II})$ and $\mathrm{Ru}($ III $)$ complexes and mixed-valence metal ( $\mathrm{Ru} /$ Fe) dimers; ${ }^{47}$ K-edge spectra of oxygen, nitrogen, and sulfur in cysteine $^{48}$ dissolved lithium polysulfide species in $\mathrm{Li}-\mathrm{S}$ batteries; ${ }^{49} \mathrm{Al}$ K-edge studies of the aluminum distribution in zeolites ${ }^{50}$ alpha-alumina, sodium aluminate, and aqueous $\mathrm{Al}^{3+}$ species; ${ }^{51} \mathrm{Cl}$ K-edge spectra in actinide hexachloride complexes $;^{52} \mathrm{Na}$ K-edge studies of the hydration structure of $\mathrm{Na}^{+} ;^{53}$ and $\mathrm{Ca} \mathrm{K}$-edge studies of supersaturated calcium carbonate solutions. ${ }^{54}$ The valence-to-core X-ray emission calculations were performed using a TDDFT-based protocol that we have developed recently. ${ }^{46}$

Our choice of DFT and TDDFT was motivated by the sizes and ensembles of the large explicitly solvated clusters\\
