\section{RESULTS AND DISCUSSION}
3.1. Structure of the Hexacyanoferrate Complexes in Water: Effects of Hydration. To study the solvent structures of the two solute ions, we have calculated the pair-distribution function, $g(r)$, which is defined as: $g(r)=n(r) / 4 \pi \rho r^{2} \delta r$, where $n(r)$ is the mean number of atoms in a shell of width $\delta r$ at distance $r$ and $\rho$ is the mean atom density. Comparing the pair distribution functions for the $\mathrm{Fe}$ (II) and $\mathrm{Fe}$ (III) complexes in Figure 1a, we see a major peak for the first water molecule shell of the $\mathrm{Fe}$ (II) complex at $\sim 4.3$ and at $\sim 4.5 \AA$ for the $\mathrm{Fe}$ (III) complex. This suggests that the first shell of water molecules is closer to the $\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}$ center compared with the $\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}$ center, and this finding has also been noted in other MD simulations. ${ }^{3,7}$ The mass-weighted density plots $(r<6.0 \AA)$ calculated over 4000 frames, as shown in Figure $1 \mathrm{~d}, \mathrm{e}$, provide a $3 \mathrm{D}$ representation of the clear difference in the local solvation structure around the $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{II})$ and $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{III})$ complexes. The 3D representation provides a stark visual representation of the stronger interaction of the ferrous complex with the water molecules. The reason for the difference in the local solvation environment can be attributed to the stronger attraction between the more negatively charged ferrous anion (charge of -4) and the positive (hydrogen) ends of the water molecules compared with the ferric ion, which has a charge of $-3$. The difference in oxidation state of the complexes results in stronger $\pi$ back-bonding between the $\mathrm{Fe}$ atom and the cyanide ligands for the $\mathrm{Fe}$ (II) complex as compared to the $\mathrm{Fe}$ (III) complex. The difference in $\pi$ back-bonding generates a more negative cyanide ligand for the ferrous species, which explains the stronger hydrogen bonding interactions with the surrounding water molecules (Figure 1d,e).

In Figure $1 \mathrm{~b}, \mathrm{c}$, we compare the radial distribution functions for the $\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{C}$ and $\mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{N}$ bond lengths for the two complexes. Our calculations reveal that the average $\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{C}$ bond in the ferrous ion $(1.91 \pm 0.05 \AA)$ is shorter than the corresponding bond in the ferric ion $(1.94 \pm 0.04 \AA)$. The average $\mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{N}$ bond is slightly shorter for the Fe(III) complex $(1.16 \pm 0.01 \AA$ ) as compared with the $\mathrm{Fe}$ (II) complex $(1.17 \pm 0.03 \AA)$. We also find that the distance distribution of the $\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{C}$ and the $\mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{N}$ bond lengths is narrower in the ferric complex as compared to the ferrous complex, and the average $\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{C}$ angle is $90^{\circ} \pm$ $4^{\circ}$ for both complexes. For comparison, we have also performed MD simulations in an implicit solvent environment. In Figure $S 10$ of the Supporting Information, we compare the pair distribution functions of the $\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{C}$ and $\mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{N}$ bond distances with the explicit solvent $\mathrm{QM} / \mathrm{MM} M \mathrm{MD}$ simulations. In the next few sections, we will explore how the changes in the local solvation environment between the $\mathrm{Fe}$ (II) and $\mathrm{Fe}$ (III) and the disruption of the octahedral symmetry of these solvated complexes as shown by the MD simulations manifest itself in the vibrational, UV/vis, and X-ray spectra.

3.2. Hexacyanoferrate Complexes in Water: Infrared Spectra of the Cyanide Stretching Region. The experimental FTIR spectra in the $\mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{N}$ stretching region for the $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{II})$ and $\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{III})$ complexes in water are reported in Figure $2 \mathrm{a}$. The spectra show a single peak corresponding to the\\
