The simulated spectra are shown in Figure $5 c, d$ with a red shift of $10.1 \mathrm{eV}$ to match the experiment and are in reasonable agreement. For the open-shell Fe(III) species, ionization of both $\alpha$ and $\beta$ core electrons, corresponding to singlet and triplet final states, was considered for the final spectrum. For the closed-shell $\mathrm{Fe}$ (II) species, only one core ionization mode, the doublet final state, was considered. The calculations indicate that the spectra for the $\mathrm{Fe}$ (II) and $\mathrm{Fe}$ (III) species have similar features and peak assignments. The weak feature A $(\sim 7095 \mathrm{eV})$ in the calculated Fe(II) spectrum (Figure 5c) results from transitions involving the $\mathrm{N} 2 \mathrm{~s}$ orbitals $\rightarrow \mathrm{Fe} 1 \mathrm{~s}$. Feature $\mathrm{B}(\sim 7106 \mathrm{eV})$ results from transitions involving $\mathrm{C}$ and $\mathrm{N} 2 \mathrm{~s}$ orbitals $\rightarrow \mathrm{Fe} 1 \mathrm{~s}$, and feature $\mathrm{C}(\sim 7108 \mathrm{eV})$ represents the de-excitation involving the $\mathrm{N}$ sp hybrid orbitals and the $\mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{N} \pi$ orbitals $\rightarrow$ Fe 1 s. The strongest feature $\mathrm{D}(\sim 7110 \mathrm{eV})$ corresponds to transitions between the $\mathrm{C}$ sp hybrid orbitals, the $\mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{N} \pi$ orbitals, and the Fe $1 \mathrm{~s}$ core hole. The assignments for the Fe(III) spectrum are the same as those described above. The calculated spectra for the $\mathrm{Fe}$ (II) and $\mathrm{Fe}$ (III) complexes also show an additional weak feature at $7116 \mathrm{eV}$, which corresponds to quadrupole transitions between the Fe $3 \mathrm{~d}$ and $\mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{N} \pi$ orbitals $\rightarrow \mathrm{Fe} 1 \mathrm{~s}$.

The above discussion suggests that feature $C$, which directly reports on transitions from the $\mathrm{N}$ sp hybrid orbitals and the $\mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{N} \pi$ orbitals to the Fe $1 \mathrm{~s}$ core hole would be the most sensitive to solvation effects as the $\mathrm{N}$ atom in the cyanide ligand is involved in hydrogen bonding with the water molecules. The heterogeneous solute-solvent interaction results in a decreased amplitude of the $\mathrm{C}$ feature and its presence as a shoulder in the experimental and simulated spectra. Further evidence of the impact of solvation on the spectra is seen by comparing the simulated spectra using a solvated cluster, which includes explicit solute-solvent interactions with those using an implicit solvation model (see Figures S6 and S7 in the Supporting Information). The feature $\mathrm{C}$ is a distinct peak in the calculated spectra using an implicit solvation model, where the Fe(II) and Fe(III) complexes have perfect octahedral symmetry and structural heterogeneity and solute-solvent interactions are absent. We expect a greater reduction of feature $\mathrm{C}$ in the $\mathrm{Fe}$ (II) complex than the Fe(III) complex because our QM/MM MD simulations reveal that the solvent interacts more strongly with the cyanide ligands in the ferrous complex. This is demonstrated in comparison with the calculated spectra in Figure $5 \mathrm{c}, \mathrm{d}$, which shows a more distinct $\mathrm{C}$ feature in the case of the ferric species.

The experimental spectra, Figure 5a,b, shows that the ratio of the intensities of peak $B$ relative to peak $D$ is significantly higher in the ferric species. This is due to the longer $\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{C}$ bond in the Fe(III) complex arising from the difference in metal-ligand interactions upon oxidation of the metal atom. The reversal of the relative peak ratios is not observed in the calculated spectra using the explicit and implicit solvation models (Figures S6 and S7). We note that calculations with the B3LYP exchange-correlation functional in ref 44 did show the experimentally observed trends. As explained earlier, our choice of the PBE0 functional for this work was motivated by our past and ongoing work on mixed-valence transition-metal complexes. A detailed analysis of the dependence of the VtC-XES on exchange-correlation functional choice is beyond the scope of this paper.

